<font color="#FF0000">IT TAKES TIME</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr 29  1:19:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I don't know why anyone would feel that it is easy to talk to someone about their feelings concerning the Vietnam War when they are standing at The Wall.  It is almost inappropriate to speak at all during that moment.<br><br>
Let me tell a short story.  When I was stationed at DaNang, we went on TDY (temporary duty) to Bien Hoa Air Field.  While there for our first of many two-week stays, we built a volleyball court at the flight line alert station.  We also had a Vietnamese Air Force detachment right next door.  Well, after a day or two, our volleyball was missing.  We found it at the Vietnamese detachment, and stole it back.  They took it again, when they played on our court.  After stealing it back for a third time, we went over there and told them that they could use the ball any time, but we would keep it at our alert building.  <br><br>
So we had started a dialog of sorts, by playing volleyball.  On my second trip about a month later, we even began playing against each other (they won--they hae a ringer, a Vietnamese/French kid who was about 6'8&quot;, thin as a wire and could jump two feet higher than the net).  On my third trip down (that would be some interaction for almost 12 weeks) they finally invited me over for some watermelon, and we talked a bit.  I asked their impressions of the war, and the guys I was speaking with were as confused as anyone.  They couldn't give me much of an answer.<br><br>
I think what I am saying is that cross-cultural communications takes a lot of time and patience.  A raport, and a trust, has to be developed, and we have sometimes to start from a negative position.  While we have preconceived ideas of what Vietnamese are, they also have preconceived ideas of what Americans are about.  There may be a lack of trust, and perhaps a fear of betrayal (again?) toward Americans in general based upon what we feel is ancient history, but what they live with daily.<br><br>
So, &quot;doc&quot; Barry, don't feel bad about your experience.  Being there, and being open to new experiences is what learning is all about.  
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


